I run 9.x on all my old PowerMacs. In theory I might use 8.6 if
they're /really/ low on RAM - like say 32MB or less.

8.5 was the first PowerPC-only kernel and allegedly drops some of the
68k baggage. However, it's a bit buggy, so I always go straight to
8.6.

But in my experience 9.x will run fine on any modestly well-specced
PowerMac. I reckon 48M is enough and 64M is better if you can get
there. 9.1 on machines for which that's the last, or 9.2.2. With 9.2.2
you get the latest MSN Messenger and other niceties, but 9.2 will only
run on some later-model PCI PowerMacs. Given enough RAM, though, you
can take a Mac which only runs 9.1, put OS X on it with XPostFacto,
then run 9.2.2 under Classic.

