It's not the shortage of memory (by modern standards) that
I'm most worried about, but the relatively slow 75MHz CPU.

I'd like to get the computer working nicely for accessing
broadband by the ethernet port. Then I'm going to give it
to someone on Freecycle who has begged me for a net-ready
computer. It has to be reasonably functional (i.e. run a
reasonably up-to-date web browser and MSN chat client),
and above all, not give the impression of being slow.

The increased functionality of 8.5.1 or 8.6, as compared
with 8.1, will most likely make it that bit slower. The
presence of 68040 legacy code in a Fat Binary (such as
OS 8.1 itself) shouldn't make that much difference to
the running speed (if it's compiled in both 68K and PPC
opcodes, the PPC CPU will simply ignore the 68K stuff.)
