I entirely disagree with your comments, based on my own substantial
direct experience.

If you want to put the Mac online, you need the latest version, but on
a machine of that age, you may as well forget it. There /are/ no
decent modern browsers for MacOS 9 or before. There's iCab, which is a
bit flakey, IE5, which is old and tired, and WamCom, a port of Mozilla
1.3.1, which is old and tired too and also rather buggy and unstable.

All require lots of RAM and a fast CPU to have a decent stab at the
Web of 2007. I've tried it. A 333MHz G3 with 192MB of RAM works after
a fashion, painfully slowly, and delivers an unsatisfactory
experience. I last used this platform in June and it was very
unpleasant.

For MSN, you can only use the final version of the MS client - and it
/only/ runs on MacOS 9.2.2. There's a hack to run it on 9.1 but it
needs redoing every reboot so is hardly ideal. I'm not aware of *any*
3rd party clients or multiprotocol clients for OS9.

